Here's a simple C++ program that achieves this task. This program considers case sensitivity; if you want it to be case-insensitive, you'll need to modify it slightly to convert all text to the same case before comparison.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

// Function to count the occurrences of a word in a file
int countWordInFile(const std::string& fileName, const std::string& word) {
    std::ifstream file(fileName);
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file: " << fileName << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(word, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
            ++count;
            pos += word.length(); // Move past the found word to search for more
        }
    }

    file.close();
    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string fileName, word;
    std::cout << "Enter the file name: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, fileName);
    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, word); // Read word, space included

    // Remove any leading/trailing whitespace from the word
    word.erase(0, word.find_first_not_of(" \t\n\r\f\v"));
    word.erase(word.find_last_not_of(" \t\n\r\f\v") + 1);

    int count = countWordInFile(fileName, word);
    if (count >= 0)
        std::cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << count << " time(s) in the file." << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This program first prompts the user to enter the file name and the word to count. It then reads the file line by line, searching for the word using the `find` function. Each time the word is found, it increments the count. Please note that this version of the program is case-sensitive. If you need it to be case-insensitive, you should convert both the line from the file and the search word to lower or upper case before the comparison.
